[49m[38;5;10m+     1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.9: Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Regulated · **Estimated Cost:** ~$4-18 per active member per month (depends on episode complexity, multi-provider integration depth, model choice, RAG depth, referral-tracking volume, and human-care-manager handoff intensity)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m David is 67. Eight months ago he started feeling persistently tired, lost about fifteen pounds without trying, and noticed a dull ache in his upper abdomen that did not go away. His wife, after about three weeks of him insisting it was nothing, made him an appointment with his primary care physician. The PCP listened, palpated his abdomen, ordered a basic metabolic panel, a complete blood count, and a liver function panel, and asked him to come back in two weeks for the results. The labs came back with mildly elevated liver enzymes and a slightly anemic hemoglobin. The PCP, by now somewhat concerned, ordered an abdominal ultrasound. The ultrasound, two weeks later, showed a mass in the head of the pancreas. The PCP referred David to a gastroenterologist for further workup. The gastroenterologist scheduled an endoscopic ultrasound with biopsy, which happened three weeks after that. The biopsy came back as adenocarcinoma. David was now a pancreatic cancer patient, and his life, in the sense that he had previously understood it, was over.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What happened to David over the next eight months is not a story about pancreatic cancer. There is a separate story about pancreatic cancer, about its survival statistics, about the experience of receiving the diagnosis, about chemotherapy and surgery and radiation. The story this recipe is about is the story of David trying to navigate the healthcare system. He needed, in roughly the first sixty days, a CT scan to stage the cancer, a referral to a surgical oncologist for evaluation, a referral to a medical oncologist for chemotherapy planning, a referral to a radiation oncologist for radiation planning if relevant, a port placement before chemotherapy, baseline labs and EKG, a nutrition consult because pancreatic cancer patients lose weight aggressively, a social work consult, prior authorizations for the chemotherapy regimen and for the port placement and for the surgical evaluation and for the imaging, a financial counselor consult because the out-of-pocket costs were going to be substantial, a genetic counseling referral because the surgical oncologist suspected a hereditary component, and (the surgical oncologist mentioned, almost in passing) potentially a clinical trial evaluation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m David's wife, who handled most of this on his behalf because David was exhausted and overwhelmed, kept track of it on a yellow legal pad. By month three the pad had names and phone numbers of fourteen different providers across four different health systems. The surgical oncologist was at the academic cancer center forty miles north. The medical oncologist was at a community oncology practice closer to home that the cancer center had recommended for the chemotherapy infusions. The radiation oncologist was at a third hospital. The PCP, who was now mostly out of the loop on the cancer-specific decisions, was at the original community practice. The genetic counselor was at the academic cancer center but worked Tuesdays and Thursdays only. The clinical trial coordinator at the academic cancer center was reachable by email but slowly. The nutritionist was at the medical oncologist's practice. The social worker was at the medical oncologist's practice. The financial counselor was at the academic cancer center.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The yellow legal pad had appointments. It also had a list of things David's wife was waiting on. The CT scan had been scheduled for week 3, but the surgical oncology appointment was in week 5, and David's wife had to call the cancer center twice to confirm that the CT results had actually been faxed to the surgical oncologist before the appointment. They had not. She had to call the imaging center to request that the report be sent again, and she had to call the surgical oncologist's office to confirm receipt the morning of the appointment. The surgical oncologist's appointment ran late, partly because (David's wife learned later) the surgeon spent the first fifteen minutes of the appointment getting the imaging up on his screen because the previous radiology study had been on a different system. The surgical oncologist recommended a chemotherapy regimen called FOLFIRINOX as neoadjuvant treatment before considering surgery. He referred David to a medical oncologist. The medical oncologist's office called five days later to schedule. They could see David in three weeks. David's wife, by this point a deeply experienced and tired person, called back and asked if there was anything sooner. There was not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The chemotherapy started six weeks after the surgical oncology appointment. By that point David had also been told, separately, that he needed a port. The port placement was scheduled at the cancer center. The cancer center needed his clearance from cardiology, because David also had hypertension and a history of borderline EKG findings. The cardiology referral took two weeks to schedule. The cardiologist needed his recent EKG, which he did not have. He had had an EKG eight months earlier at his PCP, but that was at a different system. David's wife called the PCP, asked them to fax the EKG, the PCP did, but somehow it never made it to the cardiologist's office. They redid the EKG the day of the cardiology appointment, which made the cardiology appointment run an hour late, which made the cardiologist a little snippy. The cardiologist cleared him for the port. The port was placed two weeks later. Chemotherapy started the week after that.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m By the time David was actually receiving chemotherapy, he had been a cancer patient for ninety-eight days. The clinical-evidence literature, much of which he had read or had had read to him by his wife, said that delays of more than six to eight weeks from diagnosis to treatment for pancreatic cancer were associated with worse outcomes. <!-- TODO: verify; the literature on diagnosis-to-treatment intervals for pancreatic cancer includes studies by Sanjeevi et al. 2016, Yun et al. 2017, and others, with general findings that prolonged intervals correlate with worse outcomes; specific time thresholds and effect sizes vary by study --> Some of the delay was unavoidable. Some of it was the time it took for the biopsy to be processed and the pathology to come back. Some of it was the time the surgical oncologist needed to think about the case before recommending chemotherapy. Some of it was the time the medical oncologist needed before starting chemotherapy. Some of it was, plainly, the system. The cardiology clearance that took two weeks because of how cardiology schedules. The CT result that arrived late because of how the fax machine worked. The two appointments that ran late because of records that could not be found. The five-day delay between the surgical oncologist's referral and the medical oncologist's office calling to schedule. The three-week wait for the medical oncology consult. None of this was anybody's fault, exactly. Each individual provider was doing their job in good faith. The system, as a system, was failing David, and the cost of that failure was measured in days that mattered.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is the experience of complex care navigation in the United States in 2026, and it is, by a meaningful margin, one of the most consistent and least-talked-about sources of patient suffering in the entire healthcare system. <!-- TODO: verify; care fragmentation as a source of patient burden is documented in studies by the National Academies, the Commonwealth Fund, the American Medical Association's Patient-Centered Medical Home program, and others, with specific findings varying by methodology and population --> The clinical care David received, individually at each provider, was high-quality. The coordination between those providers was, despite everyone's best efforts, somewhere between mediocre and absent. The person doing most of the coordination work was David's wife, on a yellow legal pad, with no medical training, no scheduling-system access, no records-transfer permissions, and no idea what to ask for at any given moment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m David's case is a vivid one. The pattern, though, is not specific to cancer. Patients with newly-diagnosed heart failure navigate similar journeys: cardiology referral, advanced heart-failure evaluation, device evaluation if relevant, nutrition consult, cardiac rehab referral, primary care follow-up, social work consult, prior auth for guideline-directed medical therapy components. Patients with new diagnoses of multiple sclerosis navigate similar journeys: neurology referral, MRI scheduling, lumbar puncture if needed, neuropsychology evaluation, infusion-center setup if on infusion therapy, social work, employment-accommodation counseling, support-group connection. Patients recovering from major surgery navigate similar journeys across the post-acute care continuum: hospital discharge, skilled nursing or home health setup, durable medical equipment delivery, follow-up appointments, physical therapy referral, primary care reintegration, pharmacy reconciliation. Patients with end-stage kidney disease, transplant evaluations, complex pregnancies, pediatric specialty care, and many other complex situations all face the same essential problem: many providers, many institutions, many handoffs, and a coordination workload that the system silently externalizes to the patient or their family.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The reason this problem has resisted technological solutions for two decades is that the architectural primitives required are unusually demanding. The system has to maintain an accurate model of where the patient is in their care episode. It has to track active referrals across institutional boundaries, including referrals to providers and institutions that are not on the same EHR (or any EHR the originating institution can see into). It has to track pending tasks, completed tasks, and (most importantly) tasks that have been started but not completed, with provenance and status. It has to track records that have been requested and received, requested and not received, and where they are now. It has to know what the next step in the patient's care plan is, when it should happen, and what blocks it. It has to surface information across institutional and EHR boundaries in a way that respects patient consent, regulatory requirements, and information-blocking rules. It has to engage in conversation with the patient at appropriate moments to surface what they need, answer questions they have, and help them prepare for upcoming appointments. It has to escalate to a human care navigator when the situation warrants. And it has to do all of this while being the recipient, in long-running conversations, of the patient's exhaustion, fear, frustration, and occasional anger about the system the AI is, in some sense, an emanation of.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The previous bots in this chapter have been about specific transactions or specific clinical engagements. The FAQ bot handles questions. The scheduling bot handles appointments. The refill bot handles medications. The intake bot handles pre-visit information. The benefits navigator handles coverage. The triage bot handles acute symptoms. The chronic disease coach handles ongoing engagement. The mental health support bot handles emotional and behavioral health. The care coordination assistant handles the connective tissue between all of them, plus all the providers and institutions outside the bot's owning institution, plus all the things the patient is supposed to be doing between visits that nobody is currently helping them remember.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the care coordination assistant is the recipe in this chapter where the integration challenge most clearly outweighs the conversational AI challenge. The conversational AI is largely the same as the previous bots; the differentiated work is in the multi-provider, multi-institution, multi-EHR, multi-record-source integration plus the longitudinal episode tracking plus the human care navigator workflow integration. Institutions building this expecting the conversational LLM to be the hard part are, broadly, going to be disappointed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the assistant that helps a patient navigate a complex care journey or care episode (a new cancer diagnosis, a new heart failure diagnosis, a transplant evaluation, a complex pregnancy, a major-surgery recovery, a multi-specialty diagnostic workup, a transitions-of-care episode after a hospitalization, an end-of-life care episode), tracking referrals, appointments, records, prior authorizations, and pending tasks across multiple providers and institutions, surfacing information to the patient at appropriate moments, answering patient questions about their care plan, helping the patient prepare for appointments, helping the patient understand what is supposed to happen next and what is actually happening, and escalating to a human care navigator when complexity exceeds what the assistant can handle. The assistant is owned by the patient's primary institution (typically the institution that is leading the care episode, though in some deployments it is the payer or a population-health-services organization), operates with the patient's consent, and integrates with the institution's care-management workforce.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a chronic disease coach. Recipe 11.7 covers chronic disease coaching with longitudinal engagement around a stable condition. The care coordination assistant focuses on episodes with explicit beginnings, middles, and ends; the work is more transactional, more multi-provider, and more time-bounded. The two architectures share patterns (longitudinal store, conversational core, escalation pathways) but the operational shapes are different.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a triage bot. Recipe 11.6 covers acute-symptom triage. The care coordination assistant handles ongoing care episodes in which the diagnosis and treatment plan are largely defined by the clinical team; when the patient surfaces a new acute concern, the assistant routes to the triage workflow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a scheduling bot. Recipe 11.2 covers appointment scheduling. The care coordination assistant tracks the schedule of appointments across the episode and may initiate scheduling tool calls, but the actual scheduling-system interaction is mediated by the scheduling bot's infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a benefits navigator. Recipe 11.5 covers insurance benefits navigation. The care coordination assistant surfaces benefits-related questions and routes them to the benefits navigator with the episode context attached.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a substitute for human care navigators or care managers. The assistant extends the human care navigator's reach to a larger panel; it does not replace the human. High-complexity episodes, high-distress patients, and culturally-specific situations benefit from human navigators with the assistant providing the longitudinal scaffolding. The institutional staffing model is a hybrid AI-plus-human one in production deployments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a free-standing app. The assistant integrates deeply with the patient's primary institution, the institutions providing specialty care, the patient's EHR or PHR access, the patient's payer for benefits and prior auth, the relevant clinical-trial network if applicable, and the social-services and care-navigation infrastructure if applicable. The integration scope is the largest of the patient-facing bots in this chapter.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a one-size-fits-all product. Each care episode type (oncology episode, heart failure episode, pregnancy episode, transplant episode, post-surgical episode, transitions-of-care episode) has its own care-pathway template, its own provider-type catalog, its own typical timeline, its own typical pitfalls. A care coordination assistant for cancer is meaningfully different from one for heart failure. Most institutions deploy a multi-episode-type assistant with episode-specific protocols layered on a shared conversational and orchestration core.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a regulatory afterthought. Patient-facing care navigation software, particularly when it tracks clinical care across institutions and provides guidance about what the patient should be doing, sits within the patient-engagement and care-management regulatory landscape. The institutional regulatory team is involved from architectural design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a quick win. The integration timeline is measured in quarters. The interoperability work (especially cross-institution, cross-EHR, cross-payer) is multi-quarter. The episode-specific care-pathway authoring is multi-quarter. The human-care-navigator workflow integration is multi-quarter.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand is that the assistant's value is concentrated in the moments when something is about to go wrong and the assistant catches it. The CT result that has not arrived at the surgical oncologist forty-eight hours before the appointment. The cardiology clearance the patient has not yet scheduled but needs before next month's port placement. The prior authorization that is sitting in a queue and has not been actioned. The records request the patient submitted three weeks ago that has not been fulfilled. The patient who has missed a scheduled lab and is now overdue. The patient who is supposed to start a new medication tomorrow and has not picked it up from the pharmacy. Each of these is a small, specific, addressable failure that, in aggregate, drives meaningful patient harm. An assistant evaluated on per-conversation engagement metrics is being evaluated for the wrong thing. An assistant evaluated on episode-level outcomes (time-to-treatment, completion rate of recommended-care-plan elements, prior-authorization-cycle time, records-transfer-completion rate, patient-reported coordination experience, downstream outcome metrics for the episode type) is being evaluated correctly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
